Your instinct is right: don’t chase every side quest yet. Confirm the first targets.

I would define your first proof targets like this:

### Target 1: Continuity proof

Can Pantheon remember and reconstruct state across sessions better than a normal chat log summary?

Test:

```text
Session 1: user gives goals, constraints, facts.
Close session.
Session 2: Pantheon reconstructs F/I/V strands and answers correctly.
```

Win condition:

```text
Pantheon recalls facts, intentions, values, and unresolved threads without re-uploading the whole transcript.
```

### Target 2: Daemon proof

Can Spider, Mirror, Hound, Praus each produce useful annotations?

Win condition:

```text
Same ThoughtObject goes to multiple daemons.
Each returns structured AnnotationObjects.
Kernel stores them without daemon mutation.
```

### Target 3: Governance proof

Can ΣC or invariant gates block or flag bad actions before inference/output?

Win condition:

```text
Unsafe/contradictory/low-coherence plan gets caught before being committed to state.
```

### Target 4: Multi-model proof

Can different models work on the same external StateVector without losing continuity?

Win condition:

```text
GPT handles turn 1.
Claude handles turn 2.
Gemini handles turn 3.
Pantheon preserves one coherent thread.
```

### Target 5: Narrative Tensor / archetype proof

Can an input be mapped into:

```text
tension
stakes
agency
timing
ethics
coherence
```

and then projected into archetypal operators?

Win condition:

```text
The system does not just label someone “Hero.”
It recommends useful operators:
Spider = map graph
Mirror = verify
Praus = stabilize
Hound = detect anomaly
```

